  "text": "The bug is in ModelChoiceField.prepare_value() in django/forms/models.py. When a non-pk foreign key (to_field='code') is used, the initial value from model_to_dict is a raw scalar (the stored attname value, which is the pk). prepare_value() only handles model instances (hasattr(value, '_meta')), extracting to_field_name correctly in that case. But when a raw pk integer is passed (e.g., from model_to_dict), it falls through to super().prepare_value() unchanged, returning the pk integer. Meanwhile, ModelChoiceIterator.choice() calls prepare_value(obj) with a model instance, correctly returning the to_field value (e.g., 'US'). This mismatch causes the wrong option to be highlighted. The fix is to enhance prepare_value() to handle the case where a raw pk value is provided and to_field_name is set: look up the object by pk and return its to_field_name value, consistent with how to_python() works (which uses key = self.to_field_name or 'pk' for lookups). All changes must be in django/forms/models.py.",
